In `Source/ToolCore/Project/ProjectFile.cpp`:
```C
void ProjectFile::Save(Project* project)
{
    ...
    SharedPtr<JSONFile> jsonFile(new JSONFile(context_));

    JSONValue root = jsonFile->GetRoot();

    root.Set("version", PROJECTFILE_VERSION);
    ...
}
```
Here `JSONValue root = jsonFile->GetRoot()` should be `JSONValue& root = jsonFile->GetRoot()` to obtain a reference of the JSON root. Otherwise `jsonFile` will not contain a valid JSON value and cause an assertion fail by the JSON writer.

I encountered such assertion fails in my application that integrates the atomic editor and calls this method to save projects. The official editor does not fail on this, it appears that it does not use this method to save projects.

We have good native event handling and need a better method to define custom events in C#, the paste below works and can be improved.  Just filing the issue to staging for now, will need some design work too

One important question is whether to continue routing managed events through native event system, I think so as we'll want to be able to send events from JS/TS/C#/C++ to each other... 

Improved script events are also being worked on for TypeScript in #1302

```csharp
using System;
using AtomicEngine;

public class Spinner : CSComponent
{

    [Inspector]
    float speed = 1.0f;

    // define a custom event string
    public const string MyCustomEvent = "MyCustomEvent";

    void Start()
    {
        // subscribe to our custom event
        SubscribeToEvent(MyCustomEvent, (eventType, eventData) =>
        {
            // use the event data
            Log.Info("Hello from my custom event: " + eventData.GetUInt("MyParameter"));
        });
    }

    void Update(float timeStep)
    {
        Node.Yaw(speed * timeStep * 75.0f);

        // create some event data
        var eventData = new ScriptVariantMap();
        eventData.SetUInt("MyParameter", 42);

        // send the event
        SendEvent(MyCustomEvent, eventData);
    }
}
```
